Introduction
So far, our discussion on machine learning with texts has been mostly
focused on understanding associations between documents given their
similarities in word use.
What if our interest is more in identifying association between words
given where they show up within documents?
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 2 / 48
Introduction
The classiﬁcation, clustering, topic modeling, and structural topic
modeling tools we have discussed certainly lend themselves to such an
analysis, as we have shown.
There is, however, one important limitation, and it concerns the
common input feature they all share: the document-term matrix.
Can anyone think of what this limitation might be, if we are
interested in word-word associations?
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 3 / 48
Limitations of DTMs
The issue: DTMs do not retain any information about the order of
words within the documents.
As such, DTMs provide no information about word contexts outside
of the fact that two words may co-occur in the same document.
Further, the tools we have discussed so far are not as useful for
identifying word-word associations outside of literal term
co-occurrence. What about synonyms? Metaphors? Analogies?
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 4 / 48
Enter Word Embeddings
A new(er) set of tools that help address these limitations are word
embedding models—also known as word vector models.
The goal of a word embedding model is to establish similarities between
terms based on the extent to which they occur in similar, usually
sentence-level, contexts.
Word embeddings might establish a high degree of similarity between a
noun and a common adjective (say, “apple” and “pie”). But they may also
establish a strong similarity between words that occur in similar contexts
but not often used together (e.g., “pie” and “cake”).
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 5 / 48
Enter Word Embeddings
We ﬁnd these similarities by positioning words in a common vector space.
This is why we often call word embeddings word vectors. Each word is
represented as a vector of numbers: words with similar vectors are located
closer in the vector space. Words that are in radically diﬀerent contexts
are further away in the space.
Figure 1: Words in Vector Space
Note: Figure from Bail (n.d.).
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 6 / 48
Enter Word Embeddings
Once the words in a corpus are represented as numerical vectors, we use
some basic arithmetic to see how a word’s association to other words
changes when we “shift” the center word’s context.
Here’s a popular example: “Paris is to France as Rome is to ”
(Konicek 2018).
With properly-produced word vectors (and good data), we should be able
to get this:
France - Paris + Rome = Italy
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 7 / 48
Generating Word Embeddings
So, how do we do this?
There are several diﬀerent approaches to generating word vectors. We’ll
focus on one: global vectors, also known as GloVe models (Pennington,
Socher, and Manning 2014).
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 8 / 48

below.

Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 9 / 48
Term Co-Occurrence Matrix
The context window is simply the set of words on either side of i that we
consider to hold important information about i. So say we set the context
window to be 4 words on either side of i (the main word). Our context
words would like this for various i:
The children bounce the ball quietly in their room .
Without a bowl, the man ate the potato chips from the bag .
The speaker was dressed in their doctoral regalia ,
ready to give their speech to the graduating students.

Term Co-Occurrence Matrix
Typically, though, word j provides more information as a context word for i
when it is closer to i in the text.
In that last example, “doctoral” contextualizes “regalia” better than
“their.”

context word is from the main word (Selivanov 2018a):

discussed alongside, say, thrillers. It might mean that, but it also suggests
that horror movies and thriller movies are talked about in
contextually similar ways—–even if they are not literally talked
about together.

Mapping Contexts
Perhaps we want to visualize clusters of context words more
generally—not necessarily just those context around a target word.
We can do this using dimension reduction strategies. With a dimension
reduction tool, we take high-dimensional data—such as we have here with
our word-by-50 matric—and try to pare it down to the two or three
dimensions that maximize the amount of variance explained. For our
purposes, we want to use one of these tools to reduce our word vector
matrix to two dimensions so that we can visualize it on a 2D surface.
We will use what is called principal components analysis to do this.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 18, 2019 40 / 48

Bigrams and Up
You can also do any of these analyses with two- and three- word phrases
(and up, if you want).
If you recall, in NLP circles, we refer to two-word phrases as bigrams.
